    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-06T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-06T04:00:00-05:00" n="170"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">700.00116 M.E./39: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-06T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >January 6, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 6—10:19
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. My 9, January 3, 11 a.m.<note n="8" xml:id="d170fn8">Not printed.</note>
                    Rassmussen, Rodmans, Hansons, Millers and Owens are now in Moscow. Permission
                    for them to leave the Soviet Union has not yet been granted but the resistance
                    to their departure appears to be weakening and I believe that after the Soviet
                    authorities have exhausted all of the obstructive tactics they can think of exit
                    visas will be forthcoming.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
